text: 333638801 | TFRMC | 08202666 | | 2008759 | 5/4/2005 12:00:00 AM | CORONARY ARTERY DISEASE | Signed | DIS | Admission Date: 9/10/2005 Report Status: Signed Discharge Date: 10/2/2005 ATTENDING: REMIS , MORRIS MD ADDENDUM: DISCHARGE MEDICATIONS: Include: 1. Tylenol 650 mg p.o. q.4h. p.r.n. 2. Amiodarone 200 mg p.o. daily. 3. Enteric-coated aspirin 81 mg p.o. daily. 4. Dulcolax 10 mg PR every other day. 5. Colace 100 mg p.o. b.i.d. 6. Folate 1 mg p.o. daily. 7. Haldol 0.25 mg p.o. b.i.d. p.r.n. This medication should be used sparingly as the patient gets oversedated easily. Do not give over Haldol 0.25 mg at one time. 8. Insulin regular sliding scale subcutaneous a.c. and at bedtime. 9. Lactulose 30 mL p.o. q.i.d. p.r.n. for constipation. 10. Protonix 40 mg p.o. daily. 11. Synthroid 25 mcg p.o. daily. 12. Lisinopril 10 mg p.o. daily. 13. Metamucil sugar free one packet p.o. daily. 14. Simvastatin 80 mg p.o. at bedtime. 15. Toprol XL 100 mg p.o. b.i.d. hold if systolic blood pressure less than 100 , heart rate less than 55. 16. Diltiazem extended release 360 mg p.o. daily , hold if systolic blood pressure less than 100 , heart rate less than 55. 17. Plavix 75 mg p.o. daily , this medication should not be held for any reason. 18. Maalox chewable 1-2 tablets p.o. q.6h. p.r.n. DISPOSITION: Upon discharge , the patient will be transported to the Ardsdo Crestver Nai Memorial Health Centers where he will continue physical therapy , occupational therapy , as well as continued medication titration. Upon discharge , the patient is in stable condition tolerating p.o. intake well. He was ambulating with minimal assistance. FOLLOW-UP APPOINTMENT: The patient has follow-up appointment scheduled with Dr. Seltz on 9/10/05 at 8:50 a.m. He has follow up with Dr. Okuda , his Internal Medicine physician , on 7/9/05 at 9:00. In addition , he will follow up with Dr. Ionescu on 4/4/05 at 9:30 a.m. TO DO: Includes: 1. The patient should have his INR checked everyday. The Coumadin was initiated at 1 mg p.o. daily on 7/18/05 . The dosage may need to be titrated in order to keep an INR between a goal of 2-3. 2. The patient should be continued on an aggressive bowel regimen to avoid constipation. 3. The patient should have daily weights checked , he may require additional diuresis if he shows symptoms of volume overload including an increase in greater than 2 pounds weight gain in one day or 5 pounds weight gain in a week or shows symptoms of volume overload such as respiratory distress or increasing lower extremity edema. 4.
